Point-to-point Communication
----------------------------

Standard Mode
    MPI_Send
    MPI_Recv
    MPI_Sendrecv
    MPI_Sendrecv_c
    MPI_Sendrecv_replace
    MPI_Sendrecv_replace_c

Buffered Mode
    MPI_BSend
    MPI_BRecv
    ...

Synchronous Mode
    MPI_SSend
    MPI_SRecv
    ...

Ready Mode
    MPI_RSend
    MPI_RRecv
    ...


data conversion
    representation conversion
        little endian -> big endian
        hex floating point -> IEEE floating point
    type conversion
        real -> int

communication modes
    1. standard mode
        - generally non-local
            *locality* depends on the involvement of other processes for an
            operation to complete. if it does not depend -> local; otherwise ->
            non-local
        - MPI_Send depends on another process to call a matching MPI_Recv, vice
        - versa -> non-local

    2. buffered (B)
        > a buffered mode send operation can be started whether or not a
          matching receive has been *started*. It may complete before a
          matching receive is *started*.
        > The sender copies the message into a buffer and then sends it with a
          non-blocking send (using the same protocol as for standard send)
        - local
        - MPI_Bsend
            a temporary buffer is allocated
            copy content of send buffer into the temporary buffer
                after the copy operation, the control immediately returns to
                the caller and does not have to wait for a receive opeartion
                requested by another process to complete.
            => completion of a buffered send does not require other processes
               doing something.

    3. Synchronous (S)
        > A send that uses a synchronous mode can be started whether or not a
          matching receive was started. However, the send will complete
          successfully only if a matching receive is *started*, and the receive
          operation has started to receive the message sent by the synchronous
          send.
        > The sender sends a request-to-send message. The receiver stores this
          request. When a matching receive is *started*, the receiver sends
          back a permission-to-send message, and the sender now sends the
          message.
        - i.e., the send call only waits until a receiving call is started.
        - non-local
            because it depends on other processes to initiate a receive
            operation

    4. ready (R)
        > A send that ... may be started *only* if the matching receive is
          already started. Otherwise the operation is *erroneous* and its
          outcome is undefined.
        > The message is sent as soon as possible.
        - non-local
        - assumes the receive operation has already been called and is waiting
          for the send operation.

